'''BlueBorne''' is a generic term for several [[Vulnerability (computing)|security vulnerabilities]] affecting electronic devices involving various [[Bluetooth]] implementations in [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]],  [[Linux]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]].<ref name="ARMIS-2017">{{cite news |author=Staff |title=The Attack Vector "BlueBorne" Exposes Almost Every Connected Device |url=https://www.armis.com/blueborne/ |date=September 12, 2017 |work=Armis.com |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="ARMIS-2017-pdf">{{cite news |author=Staff |title=BlueBorne - Protecting the Enterprise from BlueBorne |url=https://go.armis.com/hubfs/BlueBorne%20Technical%20White%20Paper.pdf |format=[[PDF]] |date=September 12, 2017 |work=Armis.com |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="TC-20170912">{{cite web |last=Biggs |first=Jpohn |title=New Bluetooth vulnerability can hack a phone in 10 seconds |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/12/new-bluetooth-vulnerability-can-hack-a-phone-in-ten-seconds/ |date=September 12, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref> Many devices are affected, including [[laptop]]s, [[Autonomous car|smart cars]], [[smartphone]]s and [[Wearable technology|wearable gadgets]]. The vulnerabilities were first reported by Armis, an [[Internet of things|IoT]] security firm, on September 12, 2017.<ref name="ARMIS-2017" /><ref name="ARMIS-2017-pdf" /><ref name="WIRED-20170913">{{cite web |last=Newman |first=Lily Hay |title=Hey, Turn Bluetooth Off When You're Not Using It |url=https://www.wired.com/story/turn-off-bluetooth-security/ |date=September 13, 2017 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="Android-20170916">{{cite web |last=Hildenbrand |first=Jerry |title=Let's talk about Blueborne, the latest Bluetooth vulnerability |url=https://www.androidcentral.com/lets-talk-about-blueborne-latest-bluetooth-vulnerability |date=September 16, 2017 |work=AndroidCentral.com |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="EW-20170912">{{cite web |last=Kerner |first=Sean Michael |title=BlueBorne Bluetooth Flaws Put Billions of Devices at Risk |url=http://www.eweek.com/security/blueborne-bluetooth-flaws-put-billions-of-devices-at-risk |date=September 12, 2017 |work=[[eWeek]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref> According to Armis, ''"The BlueBorne attack vector can potentially affect all devices with Bluetooth capabilities, estimated at over 8.2 billion devices today [2017]."''<ref name="ARMIS-2017" />

== History ==
The BlueBorne security vulnerabilities were first reported by Armis, an [[Internet of things|IoT]] security firm, on September 12, 2017.<ref name="ARMIS-2017" />

== Impact ==
In 2017, BlueBorne was estimated to potentially affect over 8.2 billion devices worldwide.<ref name="ARMIS-2017" /> Many devices are affected, including [[laptop]]s, [[Autonomous car|smart cars]], [[smartphone]]s and [[Wearable technology|wearable gadgets]].<ref name="ARMIS-2017" /><ref name="ARMIS-2017-pdf" /><ref name="WIRED-20170913" /><ref name="Android-20170916" /><ref name="EW-20170912" />

== Mitigation ==
Google provides a BlueBorne vulnerability scanner from Armis for [[Android (operating system)|Android]].<ref name="GoogleApp-2017">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=BlueBorne Vulnerability Scanner by Armis - 2017 |url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.armis.blueborne_detector&hl=en |date=September 21, 2017 |work=[[Google]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref>
Procedures{{what|date=February 2018}} to help protect devices from the BlueBorne security vulnerabilities were reported by September 2017.<ref name="Cornell-20170915">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=Information on new BlueBorne security vulnerability |url=https://its.weill.cornell.edu/news-and-alerts/news/information-on-new-blueborne-security-vulnerability |date=September 15, 2017 |work=[[Cornell University]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="FM-20170913">{{cite web |last=Meyer |first=David |title=How to Check If You're Exposed to Those Scary BlueBorne Bluetooth Flaws |url=http://fortune.com/2017/09/13/armis-blueborne-bluetooth-ios-android-windows-linux/ |date=September 13, 2017 |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref><ref name="WU-20170920">{{cite web |last=Geiger |first=Erik |title="BlueBorne" Exposes Millions Of Bluetooth Devices |url=https://it.wisc.edu/news/blueborne-exposes-millions-bluetooth-devices/ |date=September 20, 2017 |work=[[Wisconsin University]] |accessdate=January 5, 2018 }}</ref>{{update after|2018|2|1}}

