{{Orphan|date=August 2016}}

In [[landscape ecology]], '''spatial configuration''' describes the spatial pattern of patches in a [[landscape]]. Most traditional spatial configuration measurements take into account aspects of patches within the landscape, including patches' size, shape, density, [[Landscape connectivity|connectivity]] and [[fractal dimension]]. Other measurements are [[pixel]]-based, such as contagion and [[lacunarity]]. Together with [[spatial composition]], spatial configuration is a basic component of landscape heterogeneity indices.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Gustafson, E.J. |title=Quantifying landscape spatial pattern: what is the state of the art? |journal=Ecosystems |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=143–156 |year=1998 |pmid= |doi= 10.1007/s100219900011}}</ref>

